snippet.textDisplay: Okay, I've kept silent on this cause these reviews are funny, they're trashing this film as it should be trashed, but they are also trashing the original musical. CATS as a stage musical is based on a book of poems by T. S. Eliott, its not a story book. Weber added a loose narrative where the various cats are interviewing for the position in the Heavyside Layer, a sort of exalted afterlife for cats. So each cat tells their story using the original poems for lyrics. Old Deuteronomy is like the elder judge, at some point he's kidnapped by Macavity, the villain. But the show must go on, so other cats tell there story and eventually Old Deuteronomy is found. Meanwhile Grisabella is a new cat in town, she's old and tattered, none of the other cats want her there, they show her no compassion. At some point she sings the iconic song, Memory, about growing old and fading like an old memory that changes over time. And out of all the cats she is chosen. CATS never had a plot, it wasn't ever meant to have one. Some Broadway shows were created just for the spectacle, there would be a dozen songs strung together with a loose story, but the show would be focused on the spectacle of music, dancing and costumes. Much like Opera. I would agree that the execution  of CATS in this form was done badly, but you cannot blame the lack of story, because it never had one in the first place!

snippet.textDisplay:
Thats...the point.
The story is that they have to sing songs that introduce themselves, in order for Old Deuteronomy(the leader cat) to choose a cat so that they can be reborn and live on as a new cat.
It's also a way to let people know what kinds of cats are trying to ascend, and make you wonder "I wonder which of these characters are going to be chosen!!"
I am by no means a critic, but if you expect people to sit there and believe your word when you say "There's no story in this movie or p l a y" you must've been twiddling your thumbs the whole time whilst being half asleep throughout the film. If you payed enough attention to listen to the songs, You'd know that there is a story to both the Play, and the Movie.
*I will admit, if they had just given these actors regular costumes, and possibly..d i d n t tone down the energy for some of the film's key songs, this would have been a decent movie, at least.*
